From this image alone, I think this structure would be classified as Ottoman post 18th century. The painted decoration includes common Ottoman motifs including vegetal/floral motifs. However, a clear Western European influence can be seen for example in the trompe l'oile marble ovals. This Western European artistic influence can be found in Ottoman architecture beginning in the 18th century.

When all the images are read together, this structure can clearly be classified as Istanbul Byzantine. Ottoman influence can be found in the crescent atop the low saucer dome and the painted decoration in the interior. The bones of the structure and its exterior decoration allude to its Byzantine origin (central plan, windows in the drum of the dome, brickwork, rounded arches, etc)
The massing of the structure generally resembles that of Hagia Sofia, an iconic Istanbul Byzantine structure.

However, the crescent and interior decoration allude to an islamic influence allowing for the classification of Istanbul Byzantine
